        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We request Band-6 observations (the standard single-continuum setup), which provide a field of view of 9 arcsec for polarization (1/3 of the primary beam of the 12m-array), covering the majority of the hourglass structure detected with the SMA (Figure 3a). With the C34-4 configuration, we obtain a resolution of 0.5 arcsec, which is sufficient to resolve the inner part of the core and the separation of 1 arcsec between the fragments (Figure 2c); the maximum recoverable scale of 7.8 arcsec approximately matches the field of view and allows to effectively sample the polarized emission with intensity variation scales no larger than ~7 arcsec (From Figure 3a). Within the field of view of the proposed observations (Figure 3a), the polarized flux at 345 GHz observed with the SMA with a 2 arcsec beam is 3--7 mJy, and the polarization degree ranges from 1% to 10%. We expect similar polarization degrees for the proposed ALMA observations. Considering the beam size and observing frequency differences between the SMA and ALMA observations, we expect that the weakest polarized emission observed with the ALMA would have a flux of 47 micro-Jy, which is calculated by multiplying 3 mJy with a factor of (0.5/2)^2 * (233/345)^3.5, where we assume a smooth distribution of the polarized emission within the 2 arcsec SMA beam (if this assumption is invalid, the sensitivity requirement is less stringent) and adopt a dust opacity index of 1.5 as measured by Chen et al. (2007) for this region. So an RMS noise level of 15 micro-Jy is required to achieve SNR ~ 3 for the weakest polarized emission.  </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
