    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>How high-mass stars form remains poorly understood. Characterizing the role of magnetic fields is a fundamental step toward a complete theory of high-mass star formation. With an observational campaign made with the SMA, we detect an hourglass magnetic field threading an outflow-rotation system in the high-mass star-forming region G240.31+0.07. It is so far the simplest case of an hourglass magnetic field in a high-mass system. Here we propose for ALMA observations of the polarized dust emission toward the central pinch of the hourglass, aimed at resolving the magnetic field structure on the core fragmentation scale. Based on our analysis of the existing data, we expect that rotation would dominate over the magnetic field on that scale, allowing the development of a toroidal magnetic field, which has significant implications on the core fragmentation and disk formation/outflow creation. With the hourglass magnetic field detected with the SMA and the expected toroidal component to be detected with the ALMA, as well as the clear kinematics, G240.31 would be an ideal laboratory to test the application of scaling up the classic low-mass star formation model to high-mass star formation.</prp:abstract>
